		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/RidingWithTheWindowDown/~3/5EHMoDXE_V0/</link>
		<comments>http://www.ridingwiththewindowdown.com/2011/06/07/criterium-du-dauphine/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 07 Jun 2011 19:36:54 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>cdoelle@gmail.com (Chris Doelle)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Cycling]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Entertainment]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Criteria du Dauphiné]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.ridingwiththewindowdown.com/2011/06/07/criterium-du-dauphine/</guid>
		<description>I know when Critérium du Dauphiné comes around, it won&amp;#8217;t be long until the Tour de France. I just love the fact that so much great world-class cycling is available on television. I can still remember when we were the only family around with satellite access. It was the Wild West of television and we [...]</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I know when Critérium du Dauphiné comes around, it won&#8217;t be long until the Tour de France.  </p>
<p>I just love the fact that so much great world-class cycling is available on television.  I can still remember when we were the only family around with satellite access. It was the Wild West of  television and we had to turn the 8 ft wide dish by hand to point to a different satellite.  It was worth it. </p>
<p>Before most in the US heard of cycling, I was watching &#8216;Le Tour&#8217; and a small start called mixed martial arts. Now, these are well known sports that are readily available on satellite and even our smart phones.  </p>
<p>Back on the subject &#8211; stage 2 of the Dauphiné was a fun one and I am soo pumped to watch all the cycling classics this year.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
