		<description>Longtime readers know I am a fan of documentaries. I especially like learning about how &amp;#8220;the man is keeping us down.&amp;#8221; Food, Inc. is not only a great lesson in that but, as someone who has taken a lot of time to educate himself on our food supply, sure to be on my suggested &amp;#8220;must [...]</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><img style="float: left; padding: 5px 5px 5px 5px;" src="http://www.chrisdoelle.com/2_movie_tix.jpg" alt="" hspace="8" align="left" />Longtime readers know I am a fan of documentaries.  I especially like learning about how &#8220;the man is keeping us down.&#8221;  <a href="http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1286537/">Food, Inc</a>. is not only a great lesson in that but, as someone who has taken a lot of time to educate himself on our food supply, sure to be on my suggested &#8220;must see&#8217;s&#8221;.</p>
<p>In light of <a href="http://www.ridingwiththewindowdown.com/2011/04/19/my-tastebuds-are-changing-my-tastebuds-are-changing/">what I am doing with the Paleo Diet</a>, this could not have been a more timely viewing.</p>
<p>Seriously, watch this film.  If it doesn&#8217;t change the way you consume food &#8211; enjoy that view of the beach (with your head buried in the sand.)</p>
<p><strong>RATING 9 out of 10</strong><br />
