		<item>
		<title>No, Google +1 is not the Facebook “Like” Killer</title>
		<link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/RidingWithTheWindowDown/~3/bW3vHbZ8SWQ/</link>
		<comments>http://www.ridingwiththewindowdown.com/2011/04/07/no-google-1-is-not-the-facebook-like-killer/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Thu, 07 Apr 2011 15:05:23 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>cdoelle@gmail.com (Chris Doelle)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Blogging]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Business & Money]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Electronics]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Friends & Family]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Internet Coolness]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[SEO]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Social Media]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[+1]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[chris doelle]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[facebook]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[fresh media works]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[google]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[google plus one]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[http://www.freshmediaworks.com]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[links]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[media]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[social]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.ridingwiththewindowdown.com/?p=2349</guid>
		<description>There has been a lot of buzz recently about the experimental addition to Google called &amp;#8220;+1.&amp;#8221; In essence, +1 is a button that appears in your search results allowing you to let the world know you &amp;#8220;like&amp;#8221; that link. Some people are saying that Google&amp;#8217;s latest foray into the social space is sure to unseat [...]</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a class="highslide" onclick="return vz.expand(this)" href="http://www.ridingwiththewindowdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/google13.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-2350" title="Google +1" src="http://www.ridingwiththewindowdown.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/google13.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="124" /></a>There has been a lot of buzz recently about the experimental addition to Google called &#8220;<strong>+1</strong>.&#8221;  In essence, +1 is a button that appears in your search results allowing you to let the world know you &#8220;like&#8221; that link.</p>
<p>Some people are saying that Google&#8217;s latest foray into the social space is sure to unseat the 800lb gorilla, Facebook.  Not so fast.  <a href="http://www.google.com">Google</a> has tried social in the past (Wave &amp; Buzz) with mixed results and while I think <strong>+1</strong> has some great potential, it has to fix a few things first.</p>
<p>The main one is how you find the results.  Currently, the item&#8217;s that you have <strong>+1&#8242;ed</strong> only appear on your personal Google Profile page &#8211; who actually goes to those?  Not many.  Once these profile pages are more widely adopted, it will be more useful but the idea of a <strong>+1</strong> is still kludgy.  Facebook&#8217;s graphical avatars for your &#8220;likes&#8221; is clearly the way to go.  Get them visual and get them out front where you don&#8217;t have to search.</p>
<p>So how do you become one of the &#8220;cool kids&#8221; and add a +1 tab to your profile that nobody sees?</p>
<p>To get started, you need to enable the <strong>+1</strong> button experimental feature in your <a href="https://profiles.google.com/cdoelle">Google Profile</a>. By default, +1 button will not visible to every <a href="https://profiles.google.com/cdoelle">Google Profile</a> user. However, you can enable it by opening the <a href="http://www.google.com/experimental/index.html">Google Experimental</a> page to activate +1 share button feature for your Google Profile.  Then, click the &#8220;Join the Experiment&#8221; button for <strong>+1</strong> button listing at the top right. This will enable <strong>+1</strong> button feature for your <a href="https://profiles.google.com/cdoelle">Google Profile</a>.</p>
<p>Now all you do is search.  You will notice a grayed out <strong>+1</strong> icon next to links.  Click on them and they light up and also are listed on your <strong>+1</strong> tab of your profile.  Simple.</p>
<p>As I said, it has great potential.  It&#8217;s just not quite there yet.</p>
<p>Chris Doelle</p>
]]></content:encoded>
